Analysis of Yield Distribution Characteristic

Why choose Log-Return?

In the economics, we have Continuously Compounded Return whose distribution is similar as normal distribution. As the definition, Continuously compounded return is what happens when the interest earned on an investment is calculated and reinvested back into the account for an infinite number of periods.

  1. One-period Simple Return: \[ 1 + R_t = \frac{P_t}{P_{t-1}} \quad or \quad P_t = P_{t-1}(1 + R_t)\]

  2. Compound Return: \[ (1 + \frac{r_t}{n})^n = (1 + \frac{r_t}{n})^\frac{n*r_t}{r_t} \]

  3. When n → ∞, the function will be continous: \[ \lim_{n \to +\infty} (1 + \frac{r_t}{n})^n = \lim_{n \to +\infty} (1 + \frac{r_t}{n})^\frac{n*r_t}{r_t} = e^{r_t} \]

  4. Because of equation 1 and 2, we use Natural logarithm: \[r_t = ln(1 + R_t) = ln(\frac{P_t}{P_{t-1}}) \]

  5. Due to Logarithmic properties: \[r_t[k] = ln[(1+R_t)(1+R_{t-1})...(1+R_{t-k+1})] = r_t + r_{t-1} + ... + r_{t-k+1} \]

From Time Series Curve, Histogram, Q-Q Plot, the stock log-return has Fat-tailed distribution.

PS: A fat-tailed distribution is a probability distribution that exhibits a large skewness or kurtosis, relative to that of either a normal distribution or an exponential distribution.

x <- coredata(diff(log(AAPL["2018/2019"]$AAPL.Adjusted)))[-1]
fBasics::basicStats(x)

In the result, Kurtosis > 3, which means it is “excess kurtosis”.

Autocorrelation Function Graph and Partial Autocorrelation Graph

acf(OpCl(AAPL))

pacf(OpCl(AAPL))

In these two graph, both autocorrelation coefficient and partial autocorrelation coefficient decay very quickly to 0.

model_arima<-auto.arima(OpCl(AAPL))
model_arima
## Series: OpCl(AAPL) 
## ARIMA(1,0,0) with zero mean 
## 
## Coefficients:
##           ar1
##       -0.0979
## s.e.   0.0175
## 
## sigma^2 estimated as 0.0002598:  log likelihood=8801.32
## AIC=-17598.63   AICc=-17598.63   BIC=-17586.46

For the forecasts from ARIMA(1,0,0) above, we need use AR(1) for forecasts.

pre_arima <- forecast(model_arima,h=30)
plot(pre_arima)

The graph means the stock price will remain around 0 in the future for some time。

Analysis in ts class

Create the week of Log-Return in 2018-11-26 to 2019-11-22

AAPL$logret <- diff(log(AAPL$AAPL.Adjusted))*100
AAPL$week <- week(format(index(AAPL)))
new_AAPL <- AAPL["2018-11-26/2019-11-22", c("logret", "week")]
new_AAPL <- as.data.frame(new_AAPL)
new_AAPL <- aggregate(logret ~ week, data = new_AAPL, sum)
new_AAPL <- rbind(new_AAPL[48:53,], new_AAPL[1:47,])
new_AAPL <- new_AAPL$logret
# Becasue 2018-12-31 and 2019-01-02 in the same week, we need to add them up.
new_AAPL[6] <- sum(new_AAPL[6], new_AAPL[7])
new_AAPL <- new_AAPL[-7]

summary(new_AAPL)
##     Min.  1st Qu.   Median     Mean  3rd Qu.     Max. 
## -11.1759  -0.5637   1.3799   0.8332   2.6292  10.5487
str(new_AAPL)
##  num [1:52] 3.59 -5.82 -1.8 -9.34 3.58 ...
head(new_AAPL)
## [1]  3.585762 -5.816020 -1.802621 -9.336019  3.583918 -5.458999
# Creating Time Series Object
logret.week <- ts(new_AAPL, frequency=52, start=c(2018, 11, 26))
str(logret.week)
##  Time-Series [1:52] from 2018 to 2019: 3.59 -5.82 -1.8 -9.34 3.58 ...
